body:
This error came up from mbed library rev 98.

Reported this bug here:
https://developer.mbed.org/questions/52463/error-397-in-Timerh-when-trying-to-compi/

Reproducible test case is below:

```
#include "mbed.h"

class foo {
    void test()
    {
        t = Timer();
    };

private:
    Timer t;
};

int main() {
}
```

Probably, this is a side effect of following change in the Timer.h.

https://github.com/mbedmicro/mbed/commit/be1f88a056fce2666a9a6d4ef39d82621925f5a3#diff-af61ddf4ed1079b078bf03959c81c50f

Actual CMSIS-RTOS implementation of RTX (version V4.61) doesn't allow to wait for several event signals to be set (in a OR-based manner). For that purpose, the only way to achieve it, is calling `signal_wait` and passing argument `signals = 0`

```
Thread t;
uint32_t timeout;
t.signal_wait(0, timeout);
```

But sometimes this isn't enough and we need to wait for specific signals and discard other ones. For example, in order to wait on signals 1 or 2, we do:

```
t.signal_wait(0,timeout);
```

But if signal 4 is set, our thread `t` becomes ready.

```
t.signal_set(4);
/// this signal wakes up thread t (and it could be unsafe if we only expect signal 1 or 2).
```

To solve this situation, I've added  a new public method to `Thread` class, called: `signal_wait_or`, and I've supported it modifying the CMSIS-RTOS implementation of RTX, providing methods like: `osSignalWaitOr` and `svcSignalWaitOr`.

So, the example shown above now will be:

```
t.signal_wait_or( (1|2), timeout);
```

Now we can ensure that thread `t` will keep waiting even if signal 4 is set.

Added functionality to clear consumed signal flags on thread waiting. Example of use:

```
Thread * _th;
// .....
// .....
// Waits for signal flag 1 or 2... 
for(;;){
  osEvent oe = _th->signal_wait((1 | 2), 0);
  if(oe.status == osEventSignal && (oe.value.signals & 1) != 0){
      _th->signal_clr(1);
     // add handling code for signal flag 1
  }
  if(oe.status == osEventSignal && (oe.value.signals & 2) != 0){
      _th->signal_clr(2);
     // add handling code for signal flag 2
  }

}
```

I want to sample multiple AIn channels and simultaneously output the values to two AOut channels.

The following code works with one ain/aout combination, but if I add the definition of the second AnalogIn/AnalogOut objects, the AOut stops working:

```
 #include "mbed.h"

int main() {

   // Combination 1
    AnalogOut aout1(PA_5);
    AnalogIn ain1(PC_0);

    // Combination 2
    AnalogOut aout2(PA_6);
    AnalogIn ain2(PC_1);

    while(1) {

        aout1.write_u16(ain1.read_u16());

        aout2.write_u16(ain2.read_u16());

        wait_ms(1); 
    }
}
```

With both combinations active, I get 0V on PA_5, no matter what is on PC_0, but PC_1 -> PA_6 is still working.

Moving the constructions into the loop partially resolves the problem, but there are artefacts in the output, maybe due to the continuous re-initialization of the DAC/ADC:

```
 #include "mbed.h"

int main() {

    while(1) {

        // Combination 1
        AnalogOut aout1(PA_5);
        AnalogIn ain1(PC_0);

        // Combination 2
        AnalogOut aout2(PA_6);
        AnalogIn ain2(PC_1);

        aout1.write_u16(ain1.read_u16());

        aout2.write_u16(ain2.read_u16());

        wait_ms(1); 
    }
}
```

Any help is appreciated.
